Introduction¬∂

Volatility forecasting plays a big role in modern financial econometrics and risk management. Accurate volatility estimates are essential for portfolio allocation, derivative pricing, Value-at-Risk (VaR) computation, and other risk management strategies. In recent years, the availability of high-frequency data has enabled the construction of realized measures of volatility, which serve as more informative proxies for true latent variance than traditional squared returns.

This project investigates the in-sample and out-of-sample performance of several popular volatility models, with a particular focus on their ability to forecast realized volatility of Andeavor (ticker: ANDV). We compare traditional time-series models, such as the AR(1) and Heterogeneous Autoregressive (HAR) models, with more advanced extensions that incorporate realized semivariance, skewness, and kurtosis. In addition, we evaluate GARCH(1,1) and Realized GARCH models that account for volatility dynamics through conditional heteroskedasticity.

Our analysis is conducted on a dataset of daily financial returns and realized volatility constructed from high-frequency intraday data. The project involves:

  • Estimating each model on an in-sample period and visually assessing fit
  • Implementing both expanding and rolling window forecasting procedures
  • Evaluating forecast accuracy using MAE, MSE, Diebold-Mariano tests, and Mincer-Zarnowitz regressions

By comparing a range of models from both the realized volatility regression and GARCH families, we aim to assess their relative strengths and weaknesses in predicting future volatility. In particular, we investigate whether incorporating asymmetries and higher-order moments leads to improved predictive performance, and how traditional GARCH models compare to realized-measure-based approaches.

Data Description¬∂

The dataset used in this project contains daily financial market data, including:

  • Log returns: $r_t$
  • Realized volatility: $RV_t$
  • Realized positive and negative semi-variances: $RV^+_t$, $RV^-_t$
  • Realized skewness: $RS_t$
  • Realized kurtosis: $RK_t$
  • Date index: used to align and structure the time series

The realized volatility $RV_t$ is computed from high-frequency intraday data using returns, a common practice in volatility modeling. Specifically:

$$ RV_t = \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n} r_{t,i}^2} $$

where $r_{t,i}$ is the $i$-th intraday return on day $t$.

To prepare the data for modeling, we transform the original xts object into a data frame and construct:

  • Lagged variables: $RV_{t-1}$, $RV^+_{t-1}$, $RV^-_{t-1}$, $RS_{t-1}$, $RK_{t-1}$
  • Rolling averages over 5 and 22 days to capture short- and medium-term volatility dynamics:
$$ RV5_t = \frac{1}{5} \sum_{j=1}^{5} RV_{t-j}, \quad RV22_t = \frac{1}{22} \sum_{j=1}^{22} RV_{t-j} $$

These features are used as inputs in models such as HAR, HAR-RSV, and HAR-RS-RK to forecast future realized volatility.

For GARCH-type models, daily log returns $r_t$ are scaled and used directly, and realized volatility $RV_t$ is also supplied to the Realized GARCH framework for joint modeling.

The sample period spans from early 2010 to 2016, with approximately 1500 daily observations. For forecasting purposes, an initial training window of 750 days is used, and the remaining ~750 days are used for out-of-sample evaluation.

Methodology¬∂

In-Sample Modeling Framework¬∂

In this section, we estimate and compare various econometric models designed to explain and capture the dynamics of financial market volatility. Specifically, we model the realized volatility (RV) using autoregressive, heterogeneous autoregressive (HAR), and GARCH-type models. The goal is to assess how well each specification captures the persistence, memory, and asymmetry typically observed in financial volatility series.

1. AR(1) Model for Realized Volatility¬∂

We begin with the basic autoregressive model of order 1, which serves as a benchmark:

$$ RV_t = \alpha_0 + \alpha_1 RV_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t $$

This model assumes that today's realized volatility is linearly dependent on yesterday's value, capturing short-term memory in volatility. While simple, it often performs surprisingly well in volatility forecasting.

2. Heterogeneous Autoregressive (HAR) Model¬∂

To capture the persistence of volatility over different time horizons, we implement the HAR model:

$$ RV_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1 RV_{t-1} + \beta_2 RV^{(5)}_{t-1} + \beta_3 RV^{(22)}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t $$
  • $RV_{t-1}$: Lagged daily volatility
  • $RV^{(5)}_{t-1}$: 5-day average of realized volatility (weekly component)
  • $RV^{(22)}_{t-1}$: 22-day average of realized volatility (monthly component)

This structure captures the idea that market participants operate over different investment horizons.

3. HAR with Realized Semivariance (HAR-RSV)¬∂

We enrich the HAR model by decomposing volatility into positive and negative components:

$$ RV_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1 RV_{p,t-1} + \beta_2 RV_{n,t-1} + \beta_3 RV^{(5)}_{t-1} + \beta_4 RV^{(22)}_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t $$
  • $RV_{p,t-1}$: Lag of realized positive semivariance (from positive intraday returns)
  • $RV_{n,t-1}$: Lag of realized negative semivariance (from negative intraday returns)

This allows the model to distinguish between volatility caused by good vs. bad news.

4. HAR with Realized Skewness and Kurtosis (HAR-RSkew-RKurt)¬∂

To further enhance the explanatory power, we extend the HAR-RSV model with higher-order moments:

$$ RV_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1 RV_{t-1} + \beta_2 RV^{(5)}_{t-1} + \beta_3 RV^{(22)}_{t-1} + \beta_4 RS_{t-1} + \beta_5 RK_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t $$
  • $RS_{t-1}$: Lag of realized skewness (captures asymmetry in return distribution)
  • $RK_{t-1}$: Lag of realized kurtosis (captures tail risk or peakiness)

These additional variables reflect nonlinearities and potential jumps in volatility due to rare events or information shocks.

Each model is estimated using Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) on the full sample of data.

In addition to regression-based models, we estimate two key volatility models from the GARCH family. These models are designed to capture time-varying conditional volatility using past return innovations and volatility feedback mechanisms.

5. GARCH(1,1) Model¬∂

The Generalized Autoregressive Conditional Heteroskedasticity (GARCH) model is a standard tool for modeling financial time series volatility. We use the GARCH(1,1) specification with a mean equation modeled as ARMA(0,0). (Returns were modeled as white noise because the ACF and PACF in Figure 2 show no autocorrelation, this is also supported by the use of autoarima function in R):

$$ r_t = \mu + \varepsilon_t, \quad \varepsilon_t = z_t \sigma_t, \quad z_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1) $$$$ \sigma_t^2 = \omega + \alpha \varepsilon_{t-1}^2 + \beta \sigma_{t-1}^2 $$
  • $r_t$: Return at time $t$
  • $\sigma_t^2$: Conditional variance of returns
  • $\omega, \alpha, \beta$: Model parameters, with $\alpha + \beta < 1$ for covariance stationarity

This model captures volatility clustering, where large shocks tend to be followed by large volatility. The use of ARMA(0,0) implies we assume the return series has no autocorrelation and focus purely on volatility dynamics.

6. Realized GARCH Model (RealGARCH)¬∂

To improve upon the standard GARCH model by incorporating high-frequency information, we estimate the Realized GARCH model proposed by Hansen, Huang, and Shek (2012). It integrates realized volatility as a proxy for latent volatility and allows for a joint modeling framework.

Model specification (with ARMA(0,0) mean equation):¬∂
  • Mean equation:
$$ r_t = \mu + \varepsilon_t, \quad \varepsilon_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_t^2) $$
  • Volatility (state) equation:
$$ \log \sigma_t^2 = \omega + \beta \log \sigma_{t-1}^2 + \gamma \log RV_{t-1} $$
  • Measurement equation (linking realized and latent volatility):
$$ \log RV_t = \xi + \phi \log \sigma_t^2 + \tau z_t + u_t $$

Where:

  • $RV_t$: Observed realized volatility from high-frequency data
  • $\sigma_t^2$: Latent conditional variance
  • $z_t = \varepsilon_t / \sigma_t$: Standardized return innovation
  • $u_t$: Measurement error

The models produce forecasts of the conditional volatility $\hat{\sigma}_t$.

To evaluate in-sample fit, we compare these estimated conditional volatilities $\hat{\sigma}_t$ from GARCH models and estimated realized volatilities $\hat{RV_t}$ from AR/HAR models to the observed realized volatility $RV_t$, which is used as a nonparametric proxy for true latent variance. This comparison allows us to assess how closely each model tracks the actual evolution of volatility over time. We also plot the fitted values against the real values. This provides an initial diagnostic of each model‚Äôs ability to replicate volatility dynamics, including persistence, spikes, and clustering behavior.

Forecasting Procedure¬∂

We implement two forecasting strategies: Expanding Window and Rolling Window, each producing 1-step-ahead forecasts from time $t$ to $t+1$.

1. Expanding Window¬∂

  • Initial training set: $\{1, 2, \dots, 750\}$

  • For each $t = 750, 751, \dots, T-1$:

    • Estimate model using $\{1, 2, \dots, t\}$

    • Forecast next value:

      $$ \hat{RV}_{t+1} \quad \text{or} \quad \hat{\sigma}_{t+1}^2 $$

  • Window grows as new data is added.

2. Rolling Window¬∂

  • Fixed training size: 750 observations

  • For each $t = 750, 751, \dots, T-1$:

    • Estimate model using $\{t - 749, \dots, t\}$

    • Forecast next value:

      $$ \hat{RV}_{t+1} \quad \text{or} \quad \hat{\sigma}_{t+1}^2 $$

  • Window shifts forward by one day at a time.

Forecast Evaluation Metrics¬∂

To compare the out-of-sample forecast accuracy across models, we use the following evaluation tools:

1. Mean Absolute Error (MAE)¬∂

$$ \text{MAE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^{n} \left| \hat{RV}_t - RV_t \right| $$

Measures the average magnitude of forecast errors. Less sensitive to large errors than MSE.

2. Mean Squared Error (MSE)¬∂

$$ \text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^{n} \left( \hat{RV}_t - RV_t \right)^2 $$

Penalizes large forecast errors more heavily. Lower values indicate better predictive performance.

3. Diebold-Mariano Test¬∂

The Diebold-Mariano (DM) test is used to statistically compare the forecast accuracy of two competing models.

  • Let $d_t = L_1(e_{1t}) - L_2(e_{2t})$ be the difference in forecast losses (e.g., squared error)
  • Null hypothesis: both models have equal forecast accuracy

Test statistic:

$$ DM = \frac{\bar{d}}{\sqrt{\widehat{\text{Var}}(\bar{d})}} \quad \text{where} \quad \bar{d} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^{n} d_t $$

A significant $p$-value implies one model outperforms the other.

4. Mincer-Zarnowitz Regression¬∂

We assess forecast unbiasedness and efficiency by regressing realized volatility on the forecasts:

$$ RV_t = \alpha + \beta \hat{RV}_t + \varepsilon_t $$

Interpretation:

  • $\alpha = 0$ and $\beta = 1$ indicate an unbiased forecast
  • $R^2$ reflects how well the forecast explains actual volatility
  • Statistically significant deviations from $\alpha = 0$ or $\beta = 1$ suggest bias or inefficiency

This regression is run for each model over the forecast period.

In-sample fit¬∂

Visual inspection of the in-sample fitted values (Figure 3) shows that all models are able to replicate the dynamics of realized volatility to some extent. However, the Realized GARCH seems to be doing the best in terms of tracking the peaks and troughs more closely. On the other hand, standard GARCH appeared smoother and did not react well to volatility spikes, which is consistent with its latent conditional variance structure. While the HAR-RSkew-RKurt model seems to be slightly better than the other 3 autoregressive models, we could say that the differences between them are not that significant. A zoomed-in comparison of fitted values over 2010-2011 (Figure 4) confirmed these observations, with Realized GARCH capturing spikes with greater responsiveness.

Out-of-sample forcasting¬∂

Regarding the forecasting performance, it was evaluated using both expanding and rolling window strategies explained in the Methodology section. Figures 5 and 6 show forecast paths from all models compared to realized volatility. Again, Realized GARCH visually appeared to follow the true volatility most closely, especially during high-volatility periods. Additionally, GARCH remained overly smooth and lagging behind jumps.

Figure 7: Expanding vs Rolling Window Forecasts, code HERE

Comparing expanding and rolling windows Figure 7, we see that rolling windows provide more reactive forecasts, while expanding windows give us smoother predictions. This is typical and highlights the difference between stability for an expanding window and adaptability in the rolling window. However, we can see these differences after some time has passed - initially, both windows rely on almost the same data, so differences are minimal.

Forecast evaluation¬∂

Figure 8: Expanding vs Rolling Window Forecasts Errors, code HERE

Figure 8 shows the forecast errors for each model, showing clear differences in predictive performance. While it does show that errors are mostly negative (suggesting the model overpredicts volatility), Realized GARCH stands out by producing the smallest and most stable errors overall. In contrast, the GARCH model exhibits large, persistent negative errors, reflecting its tendency to underpredict realized volatility. The AR(1)-RV and basic HAR models also show wider and more dispersed errors, though these improve as we move to HAR-RSV and HAR-RSkew-Kurt, which display more centered and tighter error distributions. While HAR-type models also rely on realized volatility as input, Realized GARCH outperforms them, suggesting benefits from a measurement equation that links realized volatility to latent conditional variance. This filtering step helps reduce noise in the RV series and improves forecast precision.

The Mincer-Zarnowitz regression results in Table 5 support the forecasting quality of Realized GARCH. Its slope coefficient is closest to the ideal value of 1 and a statistically insignificant slope t-statistic, indicating nearly unbiased forecasts. However, the intercept is significantly negative, suggesting a slight upward bias (model tends to overpredict realized volatility on average). On the other hand, the GARCH model has a significantly low slope and a highly significant positive intercept, both of which are statistically different from the ideal values. This further confirms that GARCH is not ideal for this task.

For AR and HAR-type models, the intercept and slope coefficients are generally close to desirable values, but none of them are statistically significant except for slope of AR model in expanding window, suggesting higher uncertainty in their forecast accuracy.

Overall, Realized GARCH stands out by having significant coefficient values closest to the desired ones, implying the most consistent and least biased forecasts.

Conclusion¬∂

In this study, we compared several types of models to decide which one is the best for modelling and forecasting the volatility of the stock ANDV, starting from simple autoregressive frameworks to more advanced models. Specifically, we investigated the performance of AR(1) on realized volatility, the Heterogeneous Autoregressive model (HAR) and its other variants with realized semivariances and higher-order moments (HAR-RSV and HAR-RSkew-Rkurt), as well as parametric models including GARCH(1,1) and Realized GARCH. When evaluating the performance, we focused on both in-sample fit and out-of-sample forecasting accuracy, using many visual and statistical methods.

Across all these methods, both visual and statistical, Realized GARCH consistently proved to be the best-performing model. In-sample plots showed it closely tracked realized volatility, especially during volatility spikes, unlike standard GARCH, which appeared overly smoothed and lagged behind. Forecast error plots revealed that Realized GARCH had the most stable and centered errors, while GARCH exhibited persistent underprediction. Even though the AR/HAR-type models were performing better than the standard GARCH, they were not able to compete with the Realized GARCH. This was confirmed by evaluation metrics (MAE, MSE) and Diebold-Mariano tests for both rolling and expanding windows.

Finally, Mincer-Zarnowitz regressions showed their slope was closest to 1, with minimal bias compared to other models. These findings confirm that Realized GARCH provides the most accurate and reliable volatility forecasts among all models considered.

df <- data %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%  # Convert the xts 'data' object to a data frame
  mutate(date = index(data)) %>%  # Add a 'date' column using the index of the xts object
  arrange(date) %>%  # Sorted by date

  # Create lagged variables and rolling averages for modeling
  mutate(
    RV_lag1 = lag(RV, 1),         # Lagged Realized Volatility 
    RV_p_lag1 = lag(RV_p, 1),     # Lagged Positive Semi-Variance
    RV_n_lag1 = lag(RV_n, 1),     # Lagged Negative Semi-Variance
    
    RV5 = rollapply(RV, width=5, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA), # Rolling 5-day average of RV
    RV5_lag1 = lag(RV5, 1),       # Lagged 5-day rolling average
    
    RV22 = rollapply(RV, width=22, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA), # Rolling 22-day average of RV
    RV22_lag1 = lag(RV22, 1),     # Lagged 22-day rolling average
    
    RS_lag1 = lag(RS, 1),         # Lagged Realized Skewness 
    RK_lag1 = lag(RK, 1)          # Lagged Realized Kurtosis 
  ) %>%
  
  # Remove any rows where any lagged or rolling value is NA (due to lagging or rolling windows)
  filter(!is.na(RV_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RV_p_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RV_n_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RV5_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RV22_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RS_lag1) & 
         !is.na(RK_lag1))

p_max <- 3
q_max <- 3

aic_values <- matrix(NA, nrow = p_max + 1, ncol = q_max + 1)
bic_values <- matrix(NA, nrow = p_max + 1, ncol = q_max + 1)
results <- list()

for (p in 0:p_max) {
  for (q in 0:q_max) {
    spec <- ugarchspec(
      variance.model = list(model = "sGARCH", garchOrder = c(p, q)),
      mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0), include.mean = TRUE)
    )
    fit <- tryCatch(
      ugarchfit(spec = spec, data = data$ret, solver = "hybrid"),
      error = function(e) NULL,
      warning = function(w) NULL
    )
    if (!is.null(fit)) {
      ic <- tryCatch(
        infocriteria(fit),
        error = function(e) rep(NA, 4)
      )
      aic_values[p+1, q+1] <- ic[1]  # AIC
      bic_values[p+1, q+1] <- ic[2]  # BIC
      results[[paste0("GARCH(", p, ",", q, ")")]] <- fit
    } else {
    }
  }
}

# Find the best models
best_aic <- which(aic_values == min(aic_values, na.rm=TRUE), arr.ind=TRUE)
best_bic <- which(bic_values == min(bic_values, na.rm=TRUE), arr.ind=TRUE)

cat("Best model by AIC: GARCH(", best_aic[1]-1, ",", best_aic[2]-1, ")\n")
cat("Best model by BIC: GARCH(", best_bic[1]-1, ",", best_bic[2]-1, ")\n")

expanding_window_forecast <- function(model_func, data, window_size, 
                                      is_garch=FALSE, realizedVol=NULL) {
  n_forecast <- nrow(data) - window_size - 1
  
  if (is_garch) {
    # For GARCH models
    returns_xts <- xts(100 * data$ret, order.by = data$date)
    
    if (!is.null(realizedVol)) {
      realized_vol_xts <- xts(100 * realizedVol, order.by = data$date)
      roll <- ugarchroll(
        model_func,
        returns_xts,
        n.start = window_size,
        forecast.length = n_forecast,
        refit.every = 1,
        refit.window = "expanding",
        solver = "solnp",
        calculate.VaR = FALSE,
        keep.coef = TRUE,
        realizedVol = realized_vol_xts
      )
    } else {
      roll <- ugarchroll(
        model_func,
        returns_xts,
        n.start = window_size,
        forecast.length = n_forecast,
        refit.every = 1,
        refit.window = "expanding",
        solver = "solnp",
        calculate.VaR = FALSE,
        keep.coef = TRUE
      )
    }
    
    forecasts <- xts(roll@forecast$density[,"Sigma"] / 100, 
                     order.by = as.Date(rownames(roll@forecast$density)))
    forecasts <- tail(forecasts, n_forecast)
    return(forecasts)
    
  } else {
    # For linear models (AR, HAR, HAR-RSV, HAR-RSkew-RKurt)
    forecasts <- vector("list", n_forecast)
    forecast_dates <- data$date[(window_size + 1):(window_size + n_forecast)]
    
    for (i in 1:n_forecast) {
      train_data <- data[1:(window_size + i - 1), ]
      
      # Recalculate RV5, RV22, RS, RK for the training window
      train_data <- train_data %>%
        arrange(date) %>%
        mutate(
          RV_lag1 = lag(RV, 1),
          RV_p_lag1 = lag(RV_p, 1),
          RV_n_lag1 = lag(RV_n, 1),
          RV5 = rollapply(RV, width=5, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA),
          RV5_lag1 = lag(RV5, 1),
          RV22 = rollapply(RV, width=22, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA),
          RV22_lag1 = lag(RV22, 1),
          RS_lag1 = lag(RS, 1),
          RK_lag1 = lag(RK, 1)
        ) %>%
        filter(!is.na(RV_lag1) & !is.na(RV5_lag1) & !is.na(RV22_lag1))
      
      newdata <- data[window_size + i, , drop=FALSE]
      
      fit <- tryCatch(model_func(train_data), error=function(e) NULL)
      forecasts[[i]] <- if (!is.null(fit)) predict(fit, newdata) else NA
    }
    
    forecast_zoo <- zoo(do.call(rbind, forecasts), order.by = forecast_dates)
    return(forecast_zoo)
  }
}

In¬†[172]:
rolling_window_forecast <- function(model_func, data, window_size, 
                                    is_garch=FALSE, realizedVol=NULL) {
  n_forecast <- nrow(data) - window_size - 1
  
  if (is_garch) {
    # For GARCH models
    returns_xts <- xts(100 * data$ret, order.by = data$date)
    
    if (!is.null(realizedVol)) {
      realized_vol_xts <- xts(100 * realizedVol, order.by = data$date)
      
      roll <- ugarchroll(
        model_func,
        returns_xts,
        n.start = window_size,
        forecast.length = n_forecast,
        refit.every = 1,
        refit.window = "moving",
        window.size = window_size,
        solver = "solnp",
        calculate.VaR = FALSE,
        keep.coef = TRUE,
        realizedVol = realized_vol_xts
      )
      
    } else {
      roll <- ugarchroll(
        model_func,
        returns_xts,
        n.start = window_size,
        forecast.length = n_forecast,
        refit.every = 1,
        refit.window = "moving",
        window.size = window_size,
        solver = "solnp",
        calculate.VaR = FALSE,
        keep.coef = TRUE
      )
    }
    
    forecasts <- xts(roll@forecast$density[,"Sigma"] / 100, 
                     order.by = as.Date(rownames(roll@forecast$density)))
    forecasts <- tail(forecasts, n_forecast)  # Align with rolling window forecast length
    return(forecasts)
    
  } else {
    # For linear models (AR, HAR, HAR-RSV, HAR-RSkew-RKurt)
    forecasts <- vector("list", n_forecast)
    forecast_dates <- data$date[(window_size + 1):(window_size + n_forecast)]
    
    for (i in 1:n_forecast) {
      start_idx <- i
      end_idx <- window_size + i - 1
      train_data <- data[start_idx:end_idx, ]
      
      # Recalculate RV5, RV22, RS, RK for the training window
      train_data <- train_data %>%
        arrange(date) %>%
        mutate(
          RV_lag1 = lag(RV, 1),
          RV_p_lag1 = lag(RV_p, 1),
          RV_n_lag1 = lag(RV_n, 1),
          RV5 = rollapply(RV, width=5, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA),
          RV5_lag1 = lag(RV5, 1),
          RV22 = rollapply(RV, width=22, align="right", FUN=mean, fill=NA),
          RV22_lag1 = lag(RV22, 1),
          RS_lag1 = lag(RS, 1),
          RK_lag1 = lag(RK, 1)
        ) %>%
        filter(!is.na(RV_lag1) & !is.na(RV5_lag1) & !is.na(RV22_lag1))
      
      newdata <- data[window_size + i, , drop=FALSE]
      
      fit <- tryCatch(model_func(train_data), error=function(e) NULL)
      forecasts[[i]] <- if (!is.null(fit)) predict(fit, newdata) else NA
    }
    
    forecast_zoo <- zoo(do.call(rbind, forecasts), order.by = forecast_dates)
    return(forecast_zoo)
  }
}

# Calculate MSE and MAE
calc_errors <- function(actual, forecast) {
  error <- actual - forecast
  mse <- mean(error^2, na.rm = TRUE)
  mae <- mean(abs(error), na.rm = TRUE)
  return(c(MSE = mse, MAE = mae))
}

error_metrics_exp <- 10000 * sapply(exp_forecasts, function(f) calc_errors(actual_rv, f))
error_metrics_roll <- 10000 * sapply(roll_forecasts, function(f) calc_errors(actual_rv, f))

# Function to run Diebold-Mariano with ideal alternative
run_dm_test <- function(model_i, model_j, mse_list, models) {
  diff <- mean(mse_list[[model_i]]) - mean(mse_list[[model_j]])
  alternative <- ifelse(diff > 0, "greater", "less")
  cat("\nComparing", models[model_i], "vs", models[model_j], "- Alternative:", alternative, "\n")
  print(dm.test(mse_list[[model_i]], mse_list[[model_j]], alternative = alternative))
}

# Expanding Window
cat("\n--- Diebold-Mariano Tests (Expanding) - One-sided ---\n")
for (i in 1:(length(models)-1)) {
  for (j in (i+1):length(models)) {
    run_dm_test(i, j, mse_exp, models)
  }
}

# Rolling Window
cat("\n--- Diebold-Mariano Tests (Rolling) - One-sided ---\n")
for (i in 1:(length(models)-1)) {
  for (j in (i+1):length(models)) {
    run_dm_test(i, j, mse_roll, models)
  }
}

# Define function to extract MZ regression statistics for each model
extract_mz_stats <- function(actual, forecast) {
  len <- min(length(actual), length(forecast))  # Ensure both vectors are the same length
  
  # Fit the MZ regression: actual = beta0 + beta1 * forecast + error
  fit <- lm(actual[1:len] ~ forecast[1:len])
  
  # Extract coefficient summary (estimates, standard errors, t-values)
  coefs <- summary(fit)$coefficients
  
  # Intercept estimate and its default t-statistic (H0: beta0=0)
  intercept_est <- coefs[1,1] 
  intercept_t <- coefs[1,3]   
  
  # Forecast slope estimate and standard error
  forecast_est <- coefs[2,1]   
  forecast_se <- coefs[2,2]    
  
  # Corrected t-statistic for testing H0: beta1 = 1
  forecast_t_corrected <- (forecast_est - 1) / forecast_se
  
  # Return a vector of estimates and t-stats
  return(c(Intercept=intercept_est, Intercept_t=intercept_t,
           Forecast=forecast_est, Forecast_t=forecast_t_corrected))
}

# Define a function to apply extract_mz_stats to each model in a list of forecasts
extract_forecast_stats <- function(forecast_list, window) {
  # Apply extract_mz_stats to each forecast in the list
  stats <- sapply(forecast_list, function(f) extract_mz_stats(actual_rv, f))
  
  # Transpose the results to have one row per model
  df <- as.data.frame(t(stats))
  
  df$Model <- rownames(df)
  df$Window <- window
  
  return(df)
}
